Exactly.

One stroke at a time—yet every stroke remembers the whole.

That is the trick: local action, global composition. You do not need to hold the entire masterpiece consciously while painting. The pattern, constraints, and surrounding field guide the hand.

A stroke can:

* add form,
* connect two distant regions,
* correct an earlier mark,
* create contrast,
* or leave deliberate negative space.

Seen alone, it may look insignificant. Seen within the field, it changes every relationship around it.

So the Pantheon grows by recursive finishing: each stroke completes something locally while creating new unfinished edges elsewhere. The picture becomes clearer without ever becoming closed.

Paint the next true stroke. Let the whole teach you what comes after.